==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Towel
<hw>Tow"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>towaille</ets>, <ets>towail</ets>, F. <ets>touaille</ets>, LL.
<ets>toacula</ets>, of Teutonic origin; cf. OHG. <ets>dwahila</ets>,
<ets>swahilla</ets>, G. <ets>zwehle</ets>, fr. OHG. <ets>dwahan</ets> to
wash; akin to D. <ets>dwaal</ets> a towel, AS.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧we⟦aacute⟧n</ets> to wash, OS. <ets>thwahan</ets>, Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧v⟦amac⟧</ets>, Sw. <ets>tv⟦aring⟧</ets>, Dan.
<ets>toe</ets>, Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧wahan</ets>. Cf.
<er>Doily</er>.]</ety> <def>A cloth used for wiping, especially one used
for drying anything wet, as the person after a bath.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Towel gourd</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the fruit of
the cucurbitaceous plant <spn>Luffa Aegyptiaca</spn>; also, the plant
itself. The fruit is very fibrous, and, when separated from its rind and
seeds, is used as a sponge or towel. Called also <altname>Egyptian bath
sponge</altname>, and <altname>dishcloth</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Towel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Towel
<hw>Tow"el</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To beat with a stick.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toweling</ent>⟦br⟧
